url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780128187791000043},
author = {Cezary Orlowski},
keywords = {Agile, PRINCE2, software project management, Scrum, Smart Cities projects},
abstract = {This chapter is entirely devoted to project management (PM) issues for open data projects in Smart Cities. We present current soft and hard PM methods and assess their suitability to deal with the complexity of IoT (Internet of Things)-oriented open data projects in Smart Cities. One cannot look at the development of systems in cities and their path to Smart Cities only from the point of view of the architecture of these systems and the development of IoT systems. First of all, important mechanisms resulting from the development of Smart Cities, which are processes of obtaining and processing open data, should be taken into account. It should also be seen that the basis for the development of Smart Cities are not long-term processes but implemented projects that are a consequence of the city’s short-term processes. Hence, these projects should be properly managed. It should also be considered to what extent reference models and IoT system architectures are closed to technology only, and to what extent they can form the basis for building a reference model of using open data from IoT devices for Smart Cities. This chapter reflects on experiences gained by IoT-fueled open data projects implemented by the author in the frame of Smart Cities. Two scientific and research projects managed using conventional (hard) approaches were presented. Also, problems with the implementation of these projects are presented, resulting from their strong innovation and at the same time the difficulties of entering these projects into the rigid framework of PM. This arrangement of presentation of PM methods was important from the point of view of analyzing the possibilities of expanding Agile methods with hard management aspects. It was also important for assessing the possibilities of reducing classical software PM methods for specific Smart Cities PM. The purpose of this chapter is to consider developing a method or modifying an existing method of managing open data projects from the IoT for Smart Cities, including reference models for development or process management discussed in this book.}
}
